hands_on_practices.problem:
In a civil registration and vital statistics system, events around delivery are recorded as either stillbirth or early neonatal death. Misclassification occurs when a true event is recorded in the wrong category, which can bias the Infant Mortality Rate (IMR). The Infant Mortality Rate (IMR) is defined as the number of deaths under age $1$ divided by the number of live births, multiplied by $1000$ to express the rate per $1000$ live births. Consider a population in which there are $L_{\text{true}}$ true live births, $S_{\text{true}}$ true stillbirths, $E_{\text{true}}$ early neonatal deaths (within the first $7$ days), and $P_{\text{true}}$ post-neonatal infant deaths (from day $28$ to under age $1$). Post-neonatal deaths are assumed to be correctly ascertained as infant deaths and do not undergo misclassification.

Suppose the misclassification probability matrix from true to recorded categories is
$$
\mathbf{M} \;=\;
\begin{bmatrix}
\pi_{SS} & \pi_{SE} \\
\pi_{ES} & \pi_{EE}
\end{bmatrix}
\;=\;
\begin{bmatrix}
0.85 & 0.15 \\
0.10 & 0.90
\end{bmatrix},
$$
where the first row corresponds to true stillbirths ($S$) recorded as stillbirth ($S$) with probability $\pi_{SS}$ and as early neonatal death ($E$) with probability $\pi_{SE}$, and the second row corresponds to true early neonatal deaths ($E$) recorded as stillbirth ($S$) with probability $\pi_{ES}$ and as early neonatal death ($E$) with probability $\pi_{EE}$. Assume the following true counts: $L_{\text{true}} = 100{,}000$, $S_{\text{true}} = 3{,}000$, $E_{\text{true}} = 1{,}500$, and $P_{\text{true}} = 500$.

Using only the core definitions of IMR and the mapping implied by $\mathbf{M}$, derive the observed IMR that would result from this misclassification, the true IMR, and then compute the absolute bias $\Delta$ defined by
$$
\Delta \;=\; \text{IMR}_{\text{obs}} \,-\, \text{IMR}_{\text{true}}.
$$
Express $\Delta$ in deaths per $1000$ live births, and round your final numeric answer to four significant figures. Do not use a percentage sign; express any proportions as decimals. The final reported quantity must be a single real number.
